               <p>1336. <persName id="def1-1336-18350511" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1336-18350511" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1336-18350511" type="surname" value="GREENY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1336-18350511" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CATHERINE GREENY</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18350511-1336-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350511-1336-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350511-1336-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>stealing, on the <rs id="t18350511-cd-193" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350511-1336-offence-1 t18350511-cd-193"></join>19th of April</rs>, 3 spoons, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18350511-name-1300" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1300" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1300" type="surname" value="BRADLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1300" type="given" value="SOPHIA AMELIA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350511-1336-offence-1 t18350511-name-1300"></join>Sophia Amelia Bradley</persName>, her mistress; and </rs>
                  <persName id="def2-1336-18350511" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1336-18350511" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1336-18350511" type="surname" value="PIEARS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1336-18350511" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH PIEARS</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18350511-1336-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350511-1336-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350511-1336-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp> for feloniously receiving the said goods, well knowing them to have been stolen, against the Statute.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1302" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1302" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1302" type="surname" value="BRADLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1302" type="given" value="SOPHIA AMELIA"></interp>SOPHIA AMELIA BRADLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and live in Thornton-row, Greenwich. The prisoner, Greeny, was my servant—I missed some table-spoons on the 22nd of April—I spoke to her about them—she had complained of being ill, and was going away on the Saturday—I said I should wish the policeman to question her, and told her to leave her box, and come again on Monday—these are my spoons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1303" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1303" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1303" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1303" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA ALLEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the servant of Mrs. Bradley—Greeny was her cook—I missed the table-spoons, and told my mistress of it—I then spoke to the prisoner—she said she did not think they were right, but she knew nothing about them—I have seen Piears at the door, speaking to her, and I recollect his coming to the house on the Friday in the Easter-week—I saw the spoons safe last, on Easter Sunday—I missed them the next morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you at church on Easter Sunday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was absent about two hours—my mistress was out also—Greeny was left at home—Piears kept company with her—he might have been in the house while I was at church—the spoons were kept in the parlour—I had seen him twice at the house speaking to Greeny—he might have gone into the parlour where the spoons were.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183505110211"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1304" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1304" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1304" type="surname" value="ADAMSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1304" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN ADAMSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant R</hi> 1.) On the 27th of April I went to Mr. Carter, a pawnbroker, and found these spoons there—I saw Greeny at Mrs. Bradley's in the afternoon—I asked her if she knew any thing about any silver spoons—she said no she did not—I asked her if she had any young man came to see her—she said yes, a young man named Piears, who lived at Chelsea, but she could not tell where—I apprehended him in the Magistrates' room while the case was proceeding against Greeny.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did he come to the room? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; he was brought by another constable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1305" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1305" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1305" type="surname" value="CARTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1305" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD CARTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker at Greenwich—I produce these table-spoons, which were pawned with me on the 20th of April for 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. by the prisoner Piears—I asked him whose they were—he said his father's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you know him before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—there were several other persons in the shop, perhaps half a dozen—it was not par<lb></lb>ticularly busy day—there was no other shopman there—there might be 150 persons come to the shop in the course of the day—I suppose there were not half a dozen of them strangers—I asked the prisoner the neces<lb></lb>sary questions, and he gave his name as Richard Grant, George-street.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350511-name-1306" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1306" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1306" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350511-name-1306" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA ALLEN</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> There were two young ladies left in the house with Greeny when I and my mistress went to church—I did not see Piears at all that day.</p>
